Follow us  @middleeast for more news on the region. Israeli shares fell the most in the Middle East amid the prospect of a fourth back-to-back election as the country grapples with the coronavirus. The TA-35 closed 1% lower, with Nice Ltd., LivePerson and Teva Pharmaceutical Industries dragging it down the most. The drafting of Israel’s 2020 budget is on hold, according to people familiar with the matter, even as disputes over the spending plan threaten to bring the government down. The country is also in the middle of a second wave of coronavirus cases. Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu warned of a possible second lockdown on Thursday. Israel Parliament Gives Government Vast Power on Virus In the Gulf, equity gauges mostly advanced. Benchmark stock indexes in Dubai and Abu Dhabi rose the most while Kuwait’s fell 0.3%. MIDDLE EASTERN MARKETS: